<Blog title="The Architecting of Autoconnections" date-created="2026-06-04">
  <p>
    Hello again, world! It has been much too long since my last update. In truth, I'd hoped to have myriad more articles
    out by now, but alas, despite my best efforts to get my act together and set internal deadlines for myself, most
    attempts failed! That is, <b><em>until today, dear reader!</em></b>
  </p>
  <p>
    You see, I found a project idea so gripping that I could not let it go until it came to life. An idea so original, so profound,
    and so simple yet completely unthought of...!
  </p>
  <h3>The Amazing Idea</h3>
  <p>
    What if you had a game where you were presented with 16 words in a 4x4 grid, and those
    words could actually be grouped together into 4 groups via some semantic linking? Like a Connection of some sort? Why of course,
    such an elegant game idea has <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/games/connections"><b><em>never</em></b> been thought of before</a> by anyone else except
    the noble and venerable Mahmoud Moursy!
  </p>
  <h3>Okay, so maybe it ain't too original...</h3>
  <p>
    You see, I love/hate the New York Times' "Connections" minigame. It's fun, it's satisfying, but in an on-demand world where
    short-form content has taken hold and fried our attention spans and shrunk our brains, there just isn't enough content, is there!?
  </p>
  <p>
    What if I don't like the puzzle because it <em><b>STINKS</b></em> and it <em><b>SUCKS!?</b></em> I'm not going to put up
    with that! What do you mean I must wait 24 hours per minigame!? I want to play as many as I want!!! I want to push a button and have
    a new puzzle synergized for me right then and there!
  </p>
  <p>
    I want more!!! <b>MORE!!!</b> <em><b>MORE!!!!</b></em>
  </p>
  <h3>...and so, he set out to make more...</h3>
  <p>
    Wait, how do you even make more? It's not like generating a sudoku or something...
    I mean, the act of piecing together connected words isn't something you can easily quantify, is it?
  </p>
  <p>
    Of course, there is a solution to quantify that which cannot be quantified. It's something that we just cannot get enough of!
    Something that has repeatedly been affirmed as "the future". Something that we all love and cherish and harbor no negative
    feelings towards whatsoever. What is this wonderful thing? It's <em class="fancy">the power of <strike>machine learning</strike> AI ✨</em>!
  </p>
  <p>
    Okay, WAIT! Before you torch me to death, I just want you to know that this kind of text-matching
    model has existed for over a decade before the words "large language model" became part of
    the general corpus.
  </p>
  <h3>So how exactly do we find <strike>close</strike> connected words?</h3>
  <p>Fortunately, people much smarter than I needed to answer this question long before I did, so they took the liberty of solving that problem for me (yay!!!) and sharing their work.</p>
  <p>
    This is actually one of the problems that Google faced tracing all the way back to the 2000s. <b><em>Why!?</em></b> Well, because someone might search for "running routes", and including the
    semantically similar "jogging routes" would improve the quality of search results, giving Google a competitive edge over other, simpler engines. It isn't just Google though --
    if a Xwitter user likes lots of posts about jogging, the algorithm would naturally want to recommend more jogging or running related posts; in short, this problem comes up <em>a lot</em>
    when you're an evil tech conglomerate and need to keep someone glued to your service.
  </p>
  <p>
    The best known solution to this problem is to take a text, and then assign that text a coordinate vector in space (an "embedding"). Pieces of text that have close coordinate vectors
    have similar meanings. Every once in a while, researchers may publish their own learned (coordinate + word) pairs for others to use and review, which is very convenient for us.
  </p>
  <p>
    For this weekend's special project, I decided to use Stanford's GloVe embeddings dataset. On their website, there is <a href="https://nlp.stanford.edu/projects/glove/">a visual representation of the coordinate idea</a>
  </p>
  <p>
    So to find close words, we just pick a random word from the embedding dataset, and then we pick words with nearby coordinates. Easy, right?
  </p>
  <h3>Cleaning up a messy dataset</h3>
  <p>
    The GloVe dataset has a few problems that do make it kind of unsuitable for this project. One of those problems is just how ridiculously large it is! The entire,
    uncompressed dataset is a whopping 5GiB on-disk! For a web project, such a large file size simply will not do!
  </p>
  <div>
    There were three things I had to clean out so that the dataset would lean out 🎤👋
    <ul class="list-disc px-4">
      <li><b>Remove non-words:</b> A big chunk of the dataset contains things like random digits, punctuation, and non-English words. Removing these cleaned out >1 million words!</li>
      <li><b>Removing repeat words:</b> By using a dictionary to see if a word was in its root form (and removing non-root words), we managed to remove >440,000 words!</li>
      <li><b>Removing rare words:</b> Nobody knows what a "leptodactylidae" is (unless you're a 🤓🤓🤓), and nobody wants it in their Connection. By removing rare words, we eliminated >50,000 words!</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <p>
    There was, however, a <em class="fancy">secret fourth category</em> that I soon found out I had to filter. It was funny enough to deserve
    its own special section, or maybe even two sections!
  </p>
  <h3>Filtering out naughty words</h3>
  <p>
    The dataset contains a very large amount of data from the internet that was trained unsupervised and unfiltered. As a result, the dataset includes
    a very large portion of naughty, disorderly words and/or word pairings. As a noble warrior of justice, I have taken it upon myself to clean these unsightly
    violations of the social order... and, like, also because this project is associated with my full legal name and stuff... wouldn't be a good look... if the
    connections turned out... freaky... 🥲
  </p>
  <p>
    This problem (also known as the Scunthrope problem) has no general solution. I managed to come up with a good-enough filter for this dataset, though. Uhh, you can look
    at the boring technical details in the condensed sections below if you want.
  </p>
  <details class="border-slate-500 pl-4 border-l-4">
    <summary class="text-slate-500">Step 1: Obtain a filter list</summary>
    <p>
      To filter out naughty words, we have to know what the naughty words are! I happened to grab the <a href="https://github.com/LDNOOBW/List-of-Dirty-Naughty-Obscene-and-Otherwise-Bad-Words">List of Dirty, Naughty, Obscene, and Otherwise Bad Words</a>
      because it was a simple newline-delimited word list.
    </p>
    <p>
      However, the filter list is partially incomplete, which makes my job a little bit harder.
    </p>
  </details>
  <details class="border-slate-500 pl-4 border-l-4">
    <summary class="text-slate-500">Step 2: Why get a better list when you can just make your filter more complicated!?</summary>
    <p>
      The filter list is quite incomplete and lacks many variants of profane words. For example, the list <em>does</em> contain "f**k" but <em>does NOT</em> contain "f**ked". So something like that
      would easily slip the cracks. So at first, only ~900 profane words were caught.
    </p>
    <p>
      Additionally, filter list doesn't compensate for punctuation or anything like that (and many profane words may be hyphenated!), so I have to normalize certain word combinations so something like
      "f**ked-up" which counts as its own word doesn't slip through the cracks.
    </p>
    <p>To tackle this, I normalized all the words in the dataset and the filter list to remove punctuation and whitespace, and then compared the words in the dataset against the normalized
      and unnormalized filter lists to ensure nothing was missing! This took us up to ~1000 profane words caught.</p>
    <p>
      Finally, I <em class="fancy">lemmatized ✨</em> all the words in the dataset (converting words into their roots, so words like jogging become jog, words like f**king become f**k) and compared
      <em>that</em> against the filter list, and that took us up to ~1200 profane words caught.
    </p>
    <p>
      Well, the lemmatizer I ended up using (which was geared mostly towards web scraping and NOT profanity-filtering) did end up missing some word roots, so I had to go back and manually
      update the filter list for the outputs that missed detection. Still, we managed to catch an additional 300 <em><b>NAUGHTY, EVIL</b></em> words, which should make the playing experience better 🤞.
    </p>
  </details>
  <details class="border-slate-500 pl-4 border-l-4">
    <summary class="text-slate-500">Step 3: Put a disclaimer on there</summary>
    <p>
      You ask me, what have I learned throughout this filtration process? That I've probably missed something. But if I've reduced the chances of an unsavory word showing up down to just 1 in 5,000 -- then that's good enough for a
      toy project like this. Still though, I'd rather not have that 1 in 5,000 chance tarnish the Moursy name. So I threw a disclaimer in there.
    </p>
  </details>
  <h3>What may never be filtered -- the curse of the embeddings</h3>
  <p>Unfortunately, the embeddings themselves have an <b><em>evil mind of their own</em></b> as I have discovered through my testing!</p>
  <p>There presently exists no accessible embedding dataset that excludes profanities or "harmful content" from its training data. Part of this is that, in order
    to be generally useful, some harmful topics must be included in the training dataset. This generates unique problems of its own, because the embedding dataset
    ends up encoding some pretty nasty word combos.</p>
  <p>By combining words that are harmless in isolation, the embedding dataset can create naughty, racist, or otherwise harmful
    word combinations.</p>
  <div>
    A few examples that it managed to conjure on its own:
    <ul class="list-disc px-4">
      <li><b>Naughty behaviour:</b> The embedding dataset managed to combine the harmless words 'showering', 'jerking', and 'squirting' together into an unholy combination to allude to a banned naughty word :(</li>
      <li><b>Racist behaviour:</b> The embedding dataset considers 'Asian' and 'daddy' to be semantically close for some reason, meaning that they are likely to end up together.</li>
      <li><b>Harmful behaviour:</b> The dataset pairs words related to suicide and self-harm close to harmless words like 'disappear' or 'erasure'.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    These observations are not wholly the fault of the researchers. The results of this learning algorithm are a reflection of the internet data that they were trained on. After all, someone may need the obscene words
    in this dataset to identify words with inappropriate subtexts, which can be used to <em>enhance</em> safety instead of offending people, so interfering with the
    data in pursuit of some social justice might not even be useful in the end.
  </p>

  <p>Yet still, for this particular project it is <em>truly</em> unfortunate that the problem of inappropriate content is nigh-unsolvable.</p>

  <h3>Summary of Savings</h3>

  <p>
    Well, by eliminating everything we just did, we managed to shrink our over two-million word dataset down to just 0.3% of its original size -- taking it from a ridiculous
    5.5GiB uncompressed down to just 16.8MiB. For the world wide web though, that's still quite heavy.
  </p>

  <p>
    Part of the problem is that each line in the embedding dataset is a string that looks like this:
