  </code>
  <p>
    The first part of the string is the word, and the next 300 decimals are floating-point coordinates that can be represented with just 4 bytes in memory.
  </p>
  <p>
    But in this string form, one floating point number can take up to 107 bytes in the excessively-rare worst-case scenario. The worst offender in this specific string is the decimal "-0.0034888", which takes up 10 bytes but can be represented with just 4.
    The shortest decimal here ("0.246") takes up 5 bytes as a string -- meaning even the best case is less efficient than a floating-point representation.
  </p>
  <p>
    If we re-encode everything into a binary file format composed of null-terminated strings followed by a 300x4 byte block of coordinates for each word, we can jump from 16.8MiB to 7.8MiB of raw data -- less than half of what we were originally at!
    If we follow it up with Brotli compression, we can further reduce that size to 5.8MiB. Almost three times friendlier than 16.8MiB!
  </p>
  <h3>Recreating the Connections UI</h3>
  <p>
    I mean word lists are cool and stuff but laypeople tend to much prefer visual things that they can look at, which means that I'd have to recreate
    the Connections interface with sufficient visual flare in order to appease the masses.
  </p>
  <p>
    To recreate all the little interactions and animations, I ended up choosing <a href="https://svelte.dev">Svelte</a> as the framework of choice because it had like 90% of the animation
    tools I already needed baked right in.
  </p>
  <p>
    After that, it was your run-of-the-mill web programming work, I suppose. I like to think that I've become quite okay-ish with web development
    and web animations, and that that is why this project went so smoothly.
  </p>
  <p>
    It is a <em>small</em> shame that the skills that I have in web design are probably the most replaceable by AI, but for
    web dev I do not shed many tears -- because I secretly consider it to be the lowliest of the programming disciplines.
  </p>
  <h2>
    So just how playable are these auto-connections!?
  </h2>
  <p>
    Well, for the most part, <a href="/funbox/autoconnections">they can sometimes even be okay!</a>
  </p>
  <p>
    Fortunately (for the last time), the original Connections game has a reputation for some pretty wack word combinations anyway, so this simulated game is just like the real thing!
  </p>
